AGI - Ukraine accuses Russia&nbsp; to disseminate "false" information on the drone attack on the Zaporizhzhia nuclear power plant controlled by Moscow.&nbsp; The head of the Ukrainian center for the fight against disinformation, Lieutenant Andriy Kovalenko, said that Russia is stepping up a "campaign of provocations and falsehood" after asserting that the Ukrainian forces attacked the plant on Sunday.
<br> Russia is attacking the station "with drones, pretending that the threat to power station and nuclear safety comes from Ukraine", said Kovalenko.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Zaporizhzhia nuclear power plant in southern Ukraine, the largest structure of this type in Europe, was occupied by Russian forces since the beginning of the invasion of February 2022.&nbsp; The Russian nuclear agency Rosatom said that on Sunday there was a series of attacks, with a drone that hit the canteen of the site, wounding three staff members, one of which "gravely".
The drones also hit a merchant port and the roof of one of the six site reactors.
The International Atomic Energy Agency (AIEA), which has experts at the plant, said that the attacks caused a "physical impact" on a reactor and caused a victim, but nuclear safety was not compromised.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Rosatom has invited Western nations and IAEA leader Rafael Grossi to " categorically condemn the attempt to aggravate the situation around the largest nuclear power plant in Europe".
Kovalenko accused Russia of "manipulate the concerns of the IAEA" and of "trying to accuse Ukraine of nuclear terrorism". A spokesman for the chief intelligence of the Ukrainian Ministry of Defence, Andriy Yusov, had previously accused Russia of endangering the power plant and carrying out "imposed attacks
&nbsp;
<h2>Cremlin,&nbsp; "dangerous provocation" drones to Zaporizhia</h2>
&nbsp; The Kremlin has defined "a very dangerous provocation" the attack of drones against the Ukrainian nuclear power plant of Zaporizhzhia, the largest in Europe and that Russia has controlled since March 2022.<br> "This is a very dangerous provocation. The employees of the International Atomic Energy Agency (Aiea) witnessed attacks," said Russian President Dmitri Peskov in his daily press conference.
<br> Peskov insisted that this situation may lead to "very negative" consequences. "Unfortunately, the Kiev regime continues its terrorist activities." And last night Ukraine denied its involvement in any military operation against the plant. "Ukrainian is not involved in any armed provocation in the premises of the nuclear power station of Zaporizhia illegally occupied by Russia", said to the daily Ukrainska Pravda the spokesman of the Ukrainian military intelligence, Andri Yusov.<br> According to the Aiea, a drone attack caused "minor" damage to one of the six reactors of the plant. Meanwhile, Russian atomic agency Rosatom reported that at least three people were injured "in the Ukrainian attack": the first of the drones fell into an area near a dining room of the establishment and wounded three employees, one of whom severely. Russia and Ukraine systematically accuse each other of using the plant for military purposes, thus threatening nuclear safety in the area and throughout the region.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>New drone attack
Russian forces hit an industrial plant in the city of Zaporizhzhia. RBC-Ukraine cites a post on Telegram of the head of the region, Ivan Fedorov. "The Russians hit an industrial plant again in Zaporizhzhia", wrote Fedorov, according to which following the Russian attack 6 people were injured.

