AGI -&nbsp; Still a 'black smoke' from negotiations for a ceasefire in Gaza> and an agreement for the release of hostages. Despite the optimism of Egypt, which spoke this morning of "significant progress on several controversial points", the delegations left the Egyptian capital once again without an agreement. Surely he left the negotiating field the representation of Hamas, but according to 'Times of Israel' also the U.S. and Israeli delegations would be going from the Egyptian capital "in the coming hours".
&nbsp;
Lights and shadows on the outcome of the 24 hours cairota. If Egypt remains optimistic and speaks of 'progress' in a final document, Israel and Hamas have 'minimized' the results of the meetings. "We still don't see an agreement on the horizon," said an Israeli official at the Ynet news site. "The distance between the parties is still great > and so far there has been nothing new," he added, pointing out that the Israeli delegation had not yet left Cairo. The official's comments arrived shortly after that even a high unidentified leader of Hamas in Gaza had denied progress in the talks, telling the Al-Mayadeen news network affiliated to Hezbollah that "until there are no progress" and blaming "the stubbornness" of Israel.
&nbsp;
The Israeli delegation was led by David Barnea, head of Mossad, and head of Shin Bet Ronen Bar. The delegation of Hamas, invited by Egypt, was led by Khalil Al-Hayya, deputy head of the terrorist group in Gaza. The other two mediators, Egypt and Qatar, > were represented respectively by Abbas Kamel, head of the Egyptian intelligence, and by the Prime Minister of Qatar, Sheikh Mohammed bin Abdulrahman Al Thani.
&nbsp;
However, Egyptian optimism persisted > and a high Egyptian official told the news site New Arab based in London, supported by Qatar, that "the agreement is approaching intensely" >, with a likely humanitarian truce during the feast of Eid al-Fitr, from 9 to 12 April, which marks the end of the sacred month of Islam, Ramadan. But it will be necessary, however, that Israel also find the political square within the country. Netanyahu is under fire of the 'falks' after the partial withdrawal of Israeli troops from southern Gaza, and right-wing parties to the government threaten: "He will not remain in his place without a large-scale attack on Rafah." In the meantime, the leader of the extreme right-wing religious, Bezalel Smotrich, called on the ministers and colleagues, members of the Knesset, for updates and consultations, who were called "urgents" precisely on the possible agreement for the liberation of hostages.
&nbsp;
<h2> Israel withdraws from the South of the Strip
< a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-07/medio-oriente-comandnate-forze-armate-ritiro-truppe-gaza-sud-ma-guerra-en-lunga-25945019/" "We are fighting this war in a different way, it is different from the previous ones," said Herzi in a press release at <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-07/sei-mesi-sangue-israele-guerra-gaza-cifre-25942186/"> six months after the Hamas attack of 7 October</a>.
&nbsp;
"The war in Gaza continues and we are far from stopping. Hamas High officials are still hidden. We'll get to them sooner or later. We are making progress, killing more and more terrorists and commanders and destroying more and more terrorist infrastructure," said the high officer.
<h2> Religious right pushes for attack on Rafah</h2>
After the withdrawal from the South of Gaza, right-wing parties threaten: "Netanyahu will not remain in his place without a large-scale attack on Rafah."<br> Sources in the Israeli right-wing parties say that there is a feeling that Netanyahu is "running war" and does not intend to keep his promises to "rovesciare Hamas" and "total victory", writes Yedioth Ahronoth.
&nbsp;
"We must hope that Netanyahu will understand that without Rafah he will not be Prime Minister." To these declarations the national security minister Itamar Ben-Gvir, said that "if the prime minister decides to end the war without a large-scale attack on Rafah to defeat Hamas, he will have no mandate to continue making the prime minister".
&nbsp;
In the meantime, the leader of the extreme right-wing religious, Bezalel Smotrich, called the ministers and colleagues, members of the Knesset, for updates and consultations, which were called "urgents" precisely on the possible agreement for the liberation of hostages, currently being defined in the talks in Cairo.&nbsp;
<h2> Killed a commander of Hezbollah in southern Lebanon
A commander of the Al Radwan elite unit of the Lebanese pro-Iranian movement Hezbollah was killed with two other militiamen in an Israeli attack on the village of Al Sultanya, in southern Lebanon. Security sources told Reuters. Hezbollah made it known from him that a member of the border town of Kafr Kila was killed "while waiting for his jihadist job". Hezbollah's positions in Kafr Kila were the subject of an Israeli missile launch. The Times of Israel.
<h2> Israeli firefighting in the West Bank
A bomb attack was carried out against a bulldozer and an Israeli military vehicle operating in the refugee camp in Balata, near Nablus in the West Bank. The video with its images, spread online, is reported by The Times of Israel, according to which the media were engaged in an ongoing Idf raid in the area.

